This is similar to confluence clustering (CONF-1554) but we have multiple sites all over the world (Minneapolis, Bangalore, Sydney, London, Singapore). Our confluence server is located in the US and performance suffers for our global offices. It would be great if there were a way to "cluster" confluence over a WAN.

True clustering with memory replication, etc. is obviously a concern with WAN latencies.  I don't like complaining without proposing a solution: a 'proxy' approach similar to how Perforce works might provide a simple solution - each request on a "proxy" server calls back to the 'master' server to check the version/update time stamp/whatever, if a new version is found it is downloaded to cache and returned to the user, otherwise the page in cache is returned to the user. Edits always happen in the master server (even if this is hidden from the user).

